    <id>2</id>
    <title>Combined summary - Prohibit Merkle Internal Node Preimages That Encode Minimal 64-Byte Transactions</title>
    <updated>2026-06-23T05:12:30.152115+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/8FEEF72A-92A3-48A9-AC49-43107D17B090@sprovoost.nl/T/#m807bb368defbd9a3666fd83525587a60f4fbafcb" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2026-06-01 17:46:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>The proposal discussed introduces a new consensus rule for Bitcoin, aiming to address the security vulnerabilities associated with Merkle Tree internal node preimages that match the byte structure of a minimal 64-byte transaction. This rule is specifically designed to counteract SPV malleability issues by invalidating blocks containing such transactions, thereby enhancing the robustness of the network against certain types of malleability attacks. The proposal also outlines a minimal C++ function for implementation, which checks for prohibited internal node preimages based on specified criteria. Additionally, it advises miners on handling potential violations during block construction, including shuffling transaction order or removing problematic transactions to produce a valid block template.
Further discussions emphasize the ongoing vulnerability in SPV verifiers and propose a more systemic solution at the consensus level rather than relying on individual security enhancements. This approach seeks to patch the security loophole beneath the usage of Merkle proofs fundamentally. It contrasts with another method that involves invalidating 64-byte transactions, clarifying that only specific systems would need modifications to reject these transactions. This distinction impacts a subset of systems, especially those not involved in securing valuable transactions, making it a practical and focused solution preferred in BIP 54.
Additionally, concerns are raised about the potential risks posed by not having strict rules against nodes containing valid transactions within their path, highlighting how this could allow an attacking miner to manipulate the scenario. The complexity of implementing specific mitigations for this issue is underlined, along with the operational dynamics within layer 2 protocols of blockchain networks, where unspent transaction outputs (UTXOs) are utilized as intermediary inputs under certain conditions. This nuanced understanding reflects the intricate balance required to maintain functionality while ensuring security across the network.
Moreover, the necessity for Simplified Payment Verification (SPV) verifiers to perform additional checks despite primarily relying on the heaviest chain is questioned, suggesting a reevaluation of standard practices in blockchain security models. This inquiry prompts a deeper examination of the role and essentiality of SPV verifiers in maintaining blockchain integrity and security.
Lastly, the discussion touches upon the utilization of artificial intelligence in drafting a Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIP), emphasizing the critical review and manual editing required to ensure accuracy and integrity in the proposal's substance. This approach demonstrates a commitment to maintaining transparency and rigor in the developmental processes of blockchain technology.</summary>
